A Data Example

Our goals are to plot the time series and create a seasonal plot for the last four years of the series.

The monthly figures for US Retail Sales, from January 1995 to December 2015 are given in US_retail_sales.xlsx.

Step 3 : Read data set

readxl is one of the newest packages for accessing Excel data with R. readxlsx function can import Excel data with format from the file extension (.xlsx).

library(readxl)
US_Retail_sales<- read_xlsx("RetailSales2018_clean.xlsx")

Sales<- US_Retail_sales$Sales

Hints for Step 4

Step 5 : Change to Time-Series Object

library(forecast)
library(quantmod)
Retail_Sales <- ts(US_Retail_sales$Sales, start = as.yearmon("1995-01"),end = as.yearmon("2015-12"),freq = 12)
head(Retail_Sales)
##           Jan      Feb      Mar      Apr      May      Jun
## 1995 147182.5 147012.7 159653.3 163605.7 170088.7 168921.7

Hints for Step 5

  • The help page of ts function can be opened by two methods: help(ts) or ?ts.

  • We can convert this data frame to a time series object by use the ts() function.

  • first argument supplies the US_Retail_sales_2 data frame and we index for just the columns with the data (we store the date-time data separately).

  • second argument supplies the start time of the period of interest. (first period in 1995-01).

  • thied argument supplies the end time of the period of interest. (last period in 2015-12).

  • fourth argument identifies the frequency, which in this case is monthly (hence 12 months in a year).

Step 6: First we plot the complete time series.

  • We use the function plot
# install.packages("forecast")
plot(Retail_Sales)

Hints for Step 6

Step 7: Produce the seasonal plot of the last 4 years.

We use the function seasonplot from the forecast package

library(forecast)
library(quantmod)
library(ggplot2)
US_Retail_sales<- readxl::read_xlsx("RetailSales2018_clean.xlsx")
Retail_Sales <- ts(US_Retail_sales$Sales, start = as.yearmon("1995-01"),end = as.yearmon("2015-12"),freq = 12)
head(Retail_Sales)
##           Jan      Feb      Mar      Apr      May      Jun
## 1995 147182.5 147012.7 159653.3 163605.7 170088.7 168921.7

Step 7: Produce the seasonal plot of the last 4 years (cont’d).

z <- window(Retail_Sales,start=c(2012,1),end=c(2015,12))
seasonplot(z,year.labels = T)

Step 7: Produce the seasonal plot of the last 4 years (cont’d).

ggseasonplot(z)+ylab("Sales ($)") +ggtitle("Seasonal plot: U.S. Monthly Retailers Sales")

Hints for Step 7

window is a generic function which extracts the subset of the object x observed between the times start and end. If a frequency is specified, the series is then re-sampled at the new frequency.

  • The help page of window function can be opened by two methods: help(window) or ?window.

  • first argument supplies the Retail_Sales a time-series

  • second argument supplies the start time of the period of interest. (first period in 2012-01).

  • third argument supplies the end time of the period of interest. (last period in 2015-12).

Exercises (1): Let’s practice!

  • Help() !
  • There are many functions in R. It is often hard to remember all the argument names and details of the functions. Luckily, every single function has a help page. Using the help pages is part of using R. The help page of a function called func can be opened by two methods: help(func) or ?func.
  • Open the help page of plot by writing ?plot directly to the console and press enter.
  • Use plot() to draw a time series plot of retail sales for 1995-2015, with time on the x axis and retail_sales on the y axis.
  • Use the information on the help page and add this main title to the plot: “Time Series Plot of Retail Sales for 1995-2015”.
  • Use seasonplot() to draw seasonplots of retail sales for 2012-2015,with time on the x axis and retail_sales on the y axis.
  • Use the information on the help page and add this main title to the plot: “Seasonplots of Retail Sales for 2012-2015”.
